04801nam a22006975i 9780801459948DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979684265  a97808014599487 a10.7591/97808014599482doi  a(DE-B1597)478687  a(OCoLC)726824298  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aMED0180002bisacsh04a616.7/4422221 aAtkins, Chloe, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMy Imaginary Illness :bA Journey into Uncertainty and Prejudice in Medical Diagnosis /cChloe Atkins. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Culture and Politics of Health Care Work00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tEditor’s Note -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Beginnings -- t2. The Original Crisis -- t3. Facing Uncertainty -- t4. Ontological Apprehensions -- t5. Diagnosis: Conversion Reaction -- t6. Credo -- t7. More Paralysis and More Psychological Remedies -- t8. A Pyrrhic Victory -- t9. Becoming a Pariah -- t10. Fire! Fire! -- t11. Love in the Midst of Ruin -- t12. Grasping at a Diagnosis, Hoping for a Cure -- t13. The Crisis Deepens -- t14. Contemplating Hemlock -- t15. Icarus -- t16. A Crisis, American Style -- t17. Gravy -- tClinical Commentary -- tBibliography -- tAbout the Authors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow Patients ThinkAt age twenty-one, Chloë Atkins began suffering from a mysterious illness, the symptoms of which rapidly worsened. Paralyzed for months at a time, she frequently required intubation and life support. She eventually became quadriplegic, dependent both on a wheelchair and on health professionals who refused to believe there was anything physically wrong with her. When test after test returned inconclusive results, Atkins's doctors pronounced her symptoms psychosomatic. Atkins was told not only that she was going to die but also that this was her own fault; they concluded she was so emotionally deranged that she was willing her own death.My Imaginary Illness is the compelling story of Atkins's decades-long battle with a disease deemed imaginary, her frustration with a succession of doctors and diagnoses, her immersion in the world of psychotherapy, and her excruciating physical and emotional journey back to wellness. As both a political theorist and patient, Atkins provides a narrative critique of contemporary medicine and its problematic handling of uncertainty and of symptoms that are not easily diagnosed or known. She convincingly illustrates that medicine's belief in evidence-based practice does not mean that individual doctors are capable of objectivity, nor that the presence of biomedical ethics invokes ethical practices in hospitals and clinics.A foreword by Bonnie Blair O'Connor, who teaches medical students how to listen to patients, and a clinical commentary by Dr. Brian David Hodges, a professor of psychiatry, enrich the book's narrative with practical guidance for medical practitioners and patients alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aConsumer Health & Fitness. 4aMedicine & Medical Issues. 7aMEDICAL / Diagnosis.2bisacsh1 aHodges, Brian D.1 aO'toole, Bonnie Blair.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080145994840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801459948423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780801459948.jpg  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MDPM  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MDPM  aEBA_EEBKALL  a